==English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /pɪl/

===Etymology 1===
From Middle Low German or Middle Dutch [[pille]] (Dutch [[pil]]), probably from Latin [[pilula]].

====Noun====
'''pill''' (''plural:'' '''pills''')

# a small [[portion]] of a [[drug]] or drugs to be taken [[oral]]ly, usually of roughly [[cylindrical]] [[shape]], and of about 1 cm [[length]] and 0.5 cm [[diameter]], often [[coat]]ed to [[prolong]] [[dissolution]]. 
#'''the pill''': a pill which [[function]]s as a [[contraceptive]]
#a contemptible or unpleasant person
# {{colloquial}} a ball
#a small piece of any substance, for example a ball of fibres formed on the surface of a textile by rubbing
# {{baseball}} {{slang}} an 1800s baseball term meaning the [[ball]]

====Translations====
*French:[[pilule]] ''f'' (1,2); [[comprimé]] (1) ''m''
*German: [[Pille]] ''f'' (1), die [[Pille]] ''f'' (2)
*Portuguese: [[pílula]] (1,2), [[comprimido]] (1)

====Related terms====
#[[tablet]]
#[[morning-after pill]]

===Etymology 2===
Latin [[pilare]] ‘depilate’, from [[pilus]] ‘hair’.

====Verb====
'''pill'''
# to [[peel]]; to remove the outer layer of [[hair]], [[skin]], or [[bark]]
# to [[pillage]]; to [[despoil]] or [[impoverish]]

